result.execSummary:
Shauna K. Jenson was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Shauna K. Jenson was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Shauna K. Jenson

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: Defendant to present herself to the Jasper County District Attorney's Office by no later than the close of business on October 16, 2015.

Case called @ 1:20 p.m. Defendant Shauna K. Jenson in court with attorney Ben Szilagyi.  Defendant Shauna K. Jenson in custody.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Fugitive criminal complaint stated. Receipt admitted - Reading waived. Atty Szilagyi - DE willing to waive her right to challenge the extradition. Defendant states she is prepared to waive extradition. Extradition colloquy entertained. Defendant admits identity and authority of State of Missouri. Court accepts waiver of extradition. Court enters order authorizing extradition to the State of Missouri. Consent, Waiver and Order of Extradition executed in the Court's presence. The court advises the defendant to let the Court know if she is not picked up within 10 days. Statement by Atty Szilagyi - is requesting a signature bond or low cash bond to allow the defendant to turn herself in.  ADA Anderson - defers to the court, confirmation with Jasper Co in Missouri that the warrant is valid and they do want the defendant extradited. The court authorizes release on a $2500 Cash Bond w/ conditions.
